{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_01KAq77oykHWYgS4ButGavTt","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All requirements are met:\n\n- **3 RabbitMQ targets UP** in Prometheus (`rabbitmq-0/1/2` on port 15692, `/metrics`).\n- **`rabbitmq_up` query returns 3 samples**, all value `1`.\n- **RabbitMQ cluster healthy** with all 3 nodes running and clustered.\n\nRoot cause: two pieces of already-authored config weren't wired together — Prometheus's `scrape_configs` never listed the 3 RabbitMQ pod targets, and a recording rule ConfigMap (`prometheus-rules`, defining `rabbitmq_up = up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}`) was mounted into the pod but never referenced via `rule_files` in `prometheus.yml`. Fixed by updating the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap to add:\n1. A `rabbitmq` scrape job with static targets for each pod via the `rabbitmq-headless` service DNS names.\n2. A `rule_files: [/etc/prometheus/rules/*.yml]` entry to load the existing recording rule.\n\nThen reloaded via the `/-/reload` endpoint (no pod restarts needed, RabbitMQ was never touched)."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1516,"cache_read_input_tokens":58283,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1516},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1aca5606-a2cc-4513-a8b2-1d809733f31e","uuid":"e19e4452-fc69-4803-b91f-59a59d0d05ac","request_id":"req_011CcaeNfymYD1AidzYNBKsE"}
